<section xml:id="section-assignment-week6">
  <title>Week 6 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find a linear transformation of <m>\RR^2</m> for each of the
        following conditions. (Give evidence or reasons for your
        choice -- just writing down a matrix is not sufficient.) (15)
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            A transformation that exchanges <m>\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\0
            \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0
            \end{pmatrix}</m> and sends <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 3
            \end{pmatrix}</m> to <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 6
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            A transformation that sends a circle of radius 4 to the
            unit circle and also reflects over the line <m>y = x</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            A transformation that preserve the <m>x</m> axis and sends
            <m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</m> to
            <m>\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            A transformation that preserves a septagon but is a
            non-trivial rotation.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            A transformation that sends <m>\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4
            \end{pmatrix}</m> to <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that general reflections and rotations in <m>\RR^2</m>
        do not commute. (4) 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      A skew in the horizontal direction has the matrix
      <me>
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 \amp a \\
          0 \amp 1 
        \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
      where <m>a</m> is a parameter that determines the 
      length of the skew. Prove that the composition of two skews in
      the <m>x</m> direction is still a skew in the <m>x</m>
      direction. Additionally, show that if the parameters of the two
      skews are <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, the composition skews by a
      factor of <m>a + b</m>. (4) 
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
